Show HN: A HTML export tool for Notion.so
text:
Hi everyone!

I've been really frustrated with the way Notion.so exports your data.

I felt like I was locked into their environment, because the exported files don't resemble the original Notion pages very well.

This HN post really motivated me to take matters into my own hands: https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=35316679

I built notionSnapshot - a HTML export tool for Notion that looks just like the original pages (it's actually a fork of loconotion if you already know that project).

Anyway - it took me longer than expected to build and I would really appreciate your feedback.

How do you handle intellectual property and trade secrets at coworking offices?
text:
I'm considering using coworking spaces. They are a fantastic solution to a problem I have, especially now that they are in so many locations. However, something is giving me pause.

The companies that run these coworking spaces are naturally in a very privileged position to learn a lot about a person's business and projects. You're under their roof, in an open space or in a glass-walled office, working under the visibility of their cameras (reasonable to assume equipped with microphones capable of picking up conversations), using their internet (likely monitored and possibly logged), and their staff is interacting with people who come to meet with you. Ultimately, if they wanted to, they could figure out exactly what you're working on and who your clients are. This isn't what's giving me pause.

In order to make this a non-issue, I assumed these companies would provide a solid statement (no loopholes) in the member contract that they won't use and won't share what they are able to learn about my business and will keep whatever they learn in confidence. But...none of the spaces I contacted offer a sufficient statement to this effect. This is what's giving me pause.

Do you use a coworking space? If so, did you find a solution to this issue? Or did you just accept the risk?

Show HN: Simple proxy router in Node.js for multi tenant server
text:
I am excited to share my latest creation: a powerful yet super simple Node.js proxy server that forwards HTTP requests to a specified port based on the request host header or domain.

I use this for running multiple processes on a single server for different domains or subdomains. It supports "hot reload" by just editing the map object in the configuration file, making updates a breeze.
